Background

In Malawi, comprehensive legal reforms of the electoral laws, which also involve the institutions tasked with elections management did not receive first priority when the country gained its multi-party democracy in 1994.

After a lot of debating, the laws were amended through various laws starting with the Electoral Act of 1998. Law making process was difficult because new elected democratically are still getting their way around the legal methodology of enacting laws.

New electoral models were debated on the floor of Parliament without amendments of laws being effected. This led to utterances by some election stakeholders based on their analyses of law making process that by the time Parliament is done debating and making new laws for electoral matters, Malawi will have moved on some more hype or season, usually around May or June of the next election season. This situation was evident during this year’s campaign period, thanks to the amendments on the laws by Parliament in the Ninth Parliament.

What laws were amended?

Parliament this year amended various laws that govern how Malawi conducts elections. The most significant amendment to the Electoral Act began after Hon.
